photos.Locality: Hayward Regional Shoreline--Winton Ave. access and parking area
photos.Observation Details: Continuing bird first found by Jerry Ting. Missing when I first arrived, but settled in very near the path after a Northern Harrier flushed the shorebird flock around 5pm, apparently in the same location it has been seen the previous few days.  Large shorebird very similar to the many nearby Marbled Godwits, but drabber, with much less orange color, plain white belly, and mostly unpatterned back. More prominent supercilium than most Marbleds. Black and white striped tail coverts. Hint of streaked underwing pattern caught in one photo of the bird preening.

Continuing bird found yesterday by Sharon Jue. Still roosting with the large mixed flock of shorebirds west of the fire station. Smaller than nearby Marbled Godwits and lacking orange tones (except on the front of the face, maybe a stain from the mud?). White supercilium, streaked as opposed to barred upperparts, black and white striped tail and rump, mostly white underparts with black streaking on the flanks. Spent most of the time tucked in but occasionally looked around or preened.

Continuing just west of the pump station at the beginning of no name trail. Peep showing uniform gray coloration, dark lores and cheek, smudgy breast band, black legs with partial webbing, short bill. Found yesterday by Jerry Ting.

Continuing at the pond visible from the community garden. Thanks to Dominik and Dan for helping me get on the bird, which stayed on the water's edge the whole time I watched it. Peep with mostly clean white underparts, scaly back lacking rufous, dark legs, strong supercilium, and stubby bill.
I spent a long time trying to turn this particularly rufous bird that was hanging out with the Sanderlings into something that wasn't a Western Sandpiper, but I think that's exactly what it is.

photos.Observation Details: In the field I was convinced that the pictured bird was the continuing Ruff because it is strikingly gray compared to the other roosting Dowitchers and it has sloppy scapulars with a scaly appearance. I never saw its bill. Now I think it's probably a Dowitcher that's late in transitioning to breeding plumage, especially because of its white supercilium, just barely visible barred rump, and similar size to the birds near it. I welcome feedback on the identification. Either way the bird was along the southern edge of the northern pond, visible from the 15mph sign.

I first saw this unusual bird foraging by itself in the back of the southernmost pool, bobbing its tail constantly. When I returned I found it again much closer to the beach hunkered down with many other shorebirds where it gave me great views because it would not move, even when the surrounding flock was flushed by a peregrine falcon.  Shorebird with very dark back with many white spots. Dark cap and eye stripe contrasted sharply with mostly white face, including strong eyebrow. Underparts were mostly white with some smudged gray on the breast. Greenish legs. Bill was slightly lighter at the base, darker at the tip.

Continuing bird on and around Hermit Rock, seen by maybe ten other birders while we were there. Small, mostly black alcid with white belly, conspicuous white eye, white line trailing eye, and orange bill. Mostly perched on the front side of Hermit Rock while we were there, sometimes being chased by Pigeon Guillemots and once entering the water briefly.

Continuing black alcid with white belly, white eye stripe, and large orange bill. It was resting on the small rock to the west of Hermit Rock when we first arrived, where it stayed for maybe five minutes while some friendly birders let me peep at it through their scope. After a bit it took flight, flew around Hermit Rock a few times, then apparently landed high up on the back side. I wasn't able to see it again after that.

Bird has not yet started molting. Dark primaries extend beyond tail. Legs shorter than nearby Forster's. Dark orange bill has only faint dark tip and is thinner than nearby Forster's.

I believe this is a juvenile common tern but I'm not confident in this ID and welcome feedback. This was the only tern present. It had a complete dark cap, unlike all of the Forster's terns I had seen earlier in the day whose masks did not wrap around the nape. The front edges of the bird's upperwings are dark. Small black bill. Tail appears all white with a shallow fork. I never saw the bird's leg color.

Spent a long time examining this still mostly alternate adult Sterna tern with dark primaries thinking it might be a Common. Bird has an almost completely black cap, including nape, except some white on the forehead just above the bill. After getting confirmation from Jerry Ting I'm switching from Forster's to Common but always happy to hear additional opinions.
